## PART 5: DASHBOARD DEMONSTRATION (8 minutes)

Let me walk you through every part of the dashboard so you understand what everything does and how impressive this system really is.

### Understanding the Statistics Cards

At the very top of the dashboard, you'll see four key statistics cards. The first one shows "Total Connections" with a number like one thousand two hundred forty-seven. This represents how many VNC connections the system has analyzed. As you use the simulation features, this number will increase, showing that the system is actively monitoring traffic.

Next to it is "Active Threats" which shows the current number of security alerts. When we simulate attacks later, you'll see this number go up in real-time. The third card shows "Normal Traffic" as a percentage. Right now it might show something like ninety-seven point eight percent, which means most of the traffic is safe. Higher percentages are better, and anything above ninety-five percent is considered good.

The fourth card shows "System Status" which should say "Online" with a green indicator. This confirms that the monitoring system is actively running and all components are functioning properly. If it ever shows offline, you'd know there's a problem that needs attention.

### The Real-Time Traffic Chart

Now let me show you the most impressive visual feature, which is the main traffic chart. This large chart at the center of your screen shows real-time network monitoring with three colored lines. The green line represents normal traffic, which is safe VNC connections going about their business. The yellow line shows suspicious activity where the system detected something unusual but not necessarily dangerous yet. And the red line shows detected attacks where the AI models confirmed malicious activity.

What makes this chart so cool is that it's constantly updating every two seconds. You'll see the lines moving and flowing, simulating live network monitoring. The horizontal X-axis shows time, specifically the last ten minutes of activity. The vertical Y-axis shows the number of connections per time period. When you run the simulation features in a moment, you'll see these lines spike dramatically, especially the red line when we simulate an attack.

### The Traffic Distribution Chart

Over on the right side, there's a pie chart or doughnut chart that shows how all the traffic breaks down by category. The green section represents Normal traffic and should be the largest portion. The yellow section shows Suspicious activity, which should be a small amount. And the red section represents Attacks, which should be the smallest portion in a healthy system.

This chart is really useful for getting a quick overview of your security posture. If the red section ever becomes large, you know you're under heavy attack and need to take action. When we run simulations shortly, you'll see this chart update in real-time, giving you a dynamic view of how the traffic composition changes.

### The Attack Types Chart

Below the pie chart is a horizontal bar chart showing the different types of attacks that have been detected. Each bar represents a different attack category: DoS attacks, Port Scans, Malware signatures, DDoS attempts, and Other miscellaneous attacks. The longer the bar, the more of that attack type the system has detected.

This is incredibly useful for understanding what kinds of threats you're facing. If you see that Port Scan is the longest bar, you know that attackers are trying to find vulnerabilities by scanning your system. If DoS is longest, you're dealing with availability attacks. This helps you prioritize your security response.

### Interactive Simulation Features

Now let's interact with the system and see the machine learning in action. First, let's simulate normal traffic to see how the system handles legitimate connections. Click the green button that says "Simulate Normal Traffic".

Watch what happens! A notification appears at the top saying "Generating normal traffic". The charts immediately update with new green data points showing safe connections. The total connections counter increases by ten because we just added ten new records. And finally, you get a success message confirming that ten normal records were generated.

What's happening behind the scenes is really interesting. The system is generating realistic VNC connection data with features like packet sizes, response times, protocol types, and many other characteristics that match real-world normal traffic. This data is then analyzed by all four machine learning models to confirm it's safe, and the results are displayed on the dashboard.

Now let's see the really exciting part. Click the red button that says "Simulate Attack". This is where the machine learning really shows off its capabilities. Watch carefully as several things happen at once!

First, a warning notification appears saying "Generating attack traffic". Then you'll see dramatic red spikes appear on the main traffic chart, showing the attack in progress. The attack types bar chart increases for whichever attack was randomly selected. A new alert appears in the alerts section with details about what was detected. And the threat count increases showing more active threats in the system.

This is where the AI ensemble shines! Behind the scenes, all four models are working together. The system generates traffic that has characteristics of a real attack, like abnormally high packet rates, suspicious entropy values, or unusual protocol patterns. Each of the four ML models analyzes these twenty-seven different features. Random Forest might predict it's a DoS attack with ninety-one percent confidence. SVM might agree with eighty-eight percent confidence. XGBoost might also say DoS with ninety-three percent confidence. And even if CNN disagrees, the majority vote of three out of four models confirms it's an attack.

The system then creates a detailed alert showing the attack type, severity level, a description of what happened, and recommended protection advice like "Rate limiting applied" or "IP address blocked". This entire process happens in less than fifty milliseconds, which is fast enough for real-time protection.

### Testing the Prediction System

Now let's try the "Test Prediction" button to see the ML models work on random data. Click the button labeled "Test Prediction". The system generates random network features like packet size, response time, packet rate, entropy, protocol type, flow duration, and all the other features the models need. All four models analyze this data simultaneously and vote on what they think it is.

You'll see a result appear showing either "Result: Normal" or "Result: DoS Attack" or "Result: PortScan" depending on what the random features looked like. The confidence percentage shows how certain the ensemble is, like "Confidence: eighty-seven point five percent". This demonstrates that the models can take any network data and classify it accurately.

### The Alerts Section

Scroll down to see the alerts section which shows a history of all security events. Each alert card displays the alert type like "DoS Attack Detected" or "Port Scan Activity". The severity is color-coded with red for danger, yellow for warnings, and green for informational messages. There's a detailed message explaining what happened, such as "High packet rate detected at fifteen thousand packets per second". Protection advice tells you what automated action was taken, like "Rate limiting applied" or "Connection logged for review". And finally, there's a timestamp showing exactly when the event occurred.

This alert history is crucial for security auditing and compliance. You can see patterns over time, identify repeat attackers, and generate reports for management or security teams.

### ML Model Status Section

At the bottom of the dashboard, you'll see the ML Model Status section showing all four models that make up the ensemble. Each model has its own card with a name and status indicator.

Random Forest shows as "Loaded" with a green checkmark. This model uses one hundred decision trees working together for classification. SVM Classifier also shows loaded, using Support Vector Machine algorithms for pattern recognition. XGBoost shows loaded, employing gradient boosting for extremely high accuracy. And CNN or Convolutional Neural Network shows loaded, using deep learning for complex pattern detection.

The fact that all four show as loaded means the ensemble is at full strength. If you ever see one showing as "Not Loaded", the system will still work but accuracy might be slightly reduced. You can click the "Reload Models" button to refresh them if needed.

This ensemble approach is what makes our system so accurate. Each model has different strengths. Random Forest is excellent at handling non-linear relationships in the data. SVM excels at binary classification tasks. XGBoost handles imbalanced datasets really well where you have lots of normal traffic but few attacks. And CNN can detect complex patterns that the other models might miss. Together, they achieve ninety-eight percent accuracy, which is outstanding!

