## PART 6: REPORTS PAGE DEMONSTRATION (3 minutes)

Now let's explore the Reports page where you can generate professional documentation. Click on "Reports" in the sidebar navigation. You'll see a professional reports center with multiple options.

The page starts with a quick summary section showing key statistics like total scans performed, threats blocked by the system, system uptime percentage, and detection accuracy. These give you a snapshot of how well the security system is performing.

Below that are six different types of reports you can generate. The Security Summary report provides a comprehensive overview of all security events, threats detected, and system performance. The Threat Analysis report gives you a detailed breakdown of attack types, source IP addresses, and recommended mitigation strategies. The Traffic Analysis report shows connection statistics, bandwidth usage, and traffic patterns over time. The ML Model Report displays performance metrics for each of the four models including accuracy, precision, and recall. The Export Data option lets you download raw data in CSV format for further analysis in Excel or other tools. And the Executive Summary creates a high-level report suitable for management presentations.

Let me show you how the PDF generation actually works. Click on "Generate PDF" for the Security Summary report. Watch as the system creates a professional document. A notification appears saying "Generating Report" and "Creating PDF document". Within a few seconds, the PDF file downloads automatically to your computer.

Open the PDF file and you'll see it's a real, working document that you can read, print, and share. The PDF has a professional header with the VNC Security Monitor branding and title. There's a generation timestamp showing when the report was created and a unique report ID for tracking purposes. The document includes formatted tables with statistics showing things like total connections analyzed, threats detected, detection accuracy, system uptime, and model status. There are detailed sections on threat overview with attack types and counts, recommendations for improving security, and traffic analysis with time-period breakdowns.

Every page has a footer with page numbers so you can reference specific sections. There's also a confidentiality notice marking it as a professional security document. This PDF actually opens and works perfectly, unlike some student projects where PDFs are broken or empty. You can use these reports for project documentation, teacher presentations, or even in a real-world setting for compliance and auditing.

The CSV export functionality is also really useful. If you click the "Traffic CSV" or "Alerts CSV" buttons, the system exports all the data in comma-separated format. You can then open these files in Microsoft Excel, Google Sheets, or any data analysis tool to perform custom analysis, create your own charts, or integrate with other systems.

